# Playwright API Testing
1️⃣ What is API Testing in Playwright?
API Testing in Playwright allows you to send HTTP requests and validate responses without opening a browser UI.
Playwright provides built-in API testing support using APIRequestContext.
It is useful for:
    1. Testing backend APIs
    2. Validating microservices
    3. Creating test data before UI tests
    4. Verifying response status , headers and body
API tests run faster than UI tests because no browser is launched.

2️⃣ Why API Testing is Important in Automation
API testing helps in:
    1. Validating backend functionality
    2. Testing services independently
    3. Creating or cleaning test data
    4. Reducing dependency on UI tests
    5. Improving test speed and stability

Example:
    Instead of creating a user through UI:
        Register -> Fill form -> Submit
    You can simply call an API:
        POST /create-user
This saves time and reduces flaky tests.

3️⃣ APIRequestContext
Playwright uses APIRequestContext to perform API request.
It is similar to browser context but for APIs
Responsibilities
----------------
1. Send HTTP requests
2. Handle authentication
3. Manage headers
4. Manage cookies
5. Return responses

4️⃣ Supported HTTP Methods
Playwright supports all common HTTP methods
Method & Purpose
----------------
1. GET -> Fetch data
2. POST -> Create new resource
3. PUT -> Update resource
4. FETCH -> Partial update
5. DELETE -> Delete resource

5️⃣ Creating API Request Context
You create a request context using Playwright request fixture.
Example:
    def test_create_user(playwright):
        request_context = playwright.request_new_context()
        response=request_context.get("https://reqres.in/api/users")
        print(response.status)
        print(response.json())

Explanation:
    Playwright.request.new_context()
Creates an API testing environment

6️⃣ GET Request Example
    def test_get_users(playwright):
        request_context = playwright.request.new_context()
        response=request_context.get("https://reqres.in/api/users?page=2")
        assert response.status == 200
    
Response validation:
    response.status
    response.json()
    response.text()

7️⃣ POST Request Example
Used to create new data.
Example:
    def test_create_user(playwright):
        request_context = playwrith.request.new_context()
        response=request_context.post(
            "https://reqres.in/api/users",
            data = {
                "username" : "user",
                "password" : "password"
            }
        )
    
    assert response.status == 201

8️⃣ Sending JSON Data
Example:
    response = request_context.post(
        "https://api.example.com/users",
        json={
            "name": "Janardhan",
            "role": "Tester"
        }
    )
Difference:
    Method & Usage
    --------------
    1. data = -> Form data
    2. json = -> JSON body

9️⃣ Reading API Response
You can read response in multiple ways.
Example:
    print(response.status)
    print(response.json())
    print(response.text())

Example response validation:
    data = response.json()
    assert data["data"][0]["id"] == 1

🔟 Sending Headers
Sometimes APIs require headers.
Example:
    response = request_context.get(
        "https://api.example.com/users",
        headers={
            "Authorization": "Bearer token123"
        }
    )

1️⃣1️⃣ Authentication in API Testing
Many APIs require authentication
Example:
    response = request_context.get(
        extra_http_headers={
            "Authorization" : "Bearer token123"
        }
    )

Now every request uses this header.

1️⃣2️⃣ Using Base URL
Instead of writing full URLs every time.
Example:
    request_context = playwright.request.new_context(
        base_url="https://api.example.com"
    )

    response = request_context.get("/users")

Result:
    https://api.example.com/users


1️⃣3️⃣ Using APIRequestContext with Pytest Fixture
Example:
    import pytest

    @pytest.fixture
    def api_context(playwright):
        return playwright.request.new_context()
    
    Test file:
        def test_get_users(api_context):

            response = api_context.get("https://reqres.in/api/users")

            assert response.status == 200
    
Benefits:
    1. Reusable
    2. Cleaner tests
    3. Better framework structure

1️⃣4️⃣ API Testing + UI Testing Combination
Playwright allows combining API + UI tests.
Example scenario:
    step1: Create user login
    step2: Login using UI
    step3: Verify user dashboard

    Example:
        API -> Create user
        UI -> Login
        UI -> Verify data
    
This makes faster and reliable

1️⃣5️⃣ Cleaning Test Data
After testing , you can remove test data using API
Example:
    request_context.delete(
        "https://api.example.com/users/10"
    )

This ensures class test environment

1️⃣6️⃣ Example Complete API Test
Example:
    def test_user_api(playwright):

        request_context = playwright.request.new_context()

        # Create user
        response = request_context.post(
            "https://reqres.in/api/users",
            json={"name": "Janardhan", "job": "QA"}
        )

        assert response.status == 201

        data = response.json()

        assert data["name"] == "Janardhan"
    
